<!-- LESSONS LEARNED -->
<section id="lessons">
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="eyebrow">Engineering Synthesis</div>
    <h2>Lessons Learned</h2>
    <div class="lessons-grid">

      <div class="lesson-item">
        <div class="lesson-num">01</div>
        <div>
          <div class="lesson-title">A CLAUDE.md encoding architecture is worth more than a wiki</div>
          <p class="lesson-body">
            koel's CLAUDE.md explicitly prohibits config() calls in services, requires repositories to be read-only,
            and mandates throw_if over bare throw. These are actionable, checkable rules — not documentation that
            describes what code does, but rules that constrain what code may do. Every other project has either no
            documentation or prose that rots as the codebase evolves. The CLAUDE.md approach makes architecture
            refusals automatic rather than opinion-based, for AI agents and human contributors equally.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="lesson-item">
        <div class="lesson-num">02</div>
        <div>
          <div class="lesson-title">PHPStan level matters more than its presence</div>
          <p class="lesson-body">
            Level 4 with broad suppressions may be worse than no PHPStan — it signals "we have static analysis"
            while hiding the same bugs it would catch at level 6. The false confidence is the hazard. The projects
            with the fewest code quality issues (koel, subscriptionify, monica) all run at genuinely enforced levels.
            One finding type matters most: "Call to an undefined method" must never be suppressed across an entire
            codebase — especially in financial applications.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="lesson-item">
        <div class="lesson-num">03</div>
        <div>
          <div class="lesson-title">The Action pattern moves the God class — it doesn't kill it</div>
          <p class="lesson-body">
            Every project that adopted Action classes (coolify, laraowl, koel) is better for it — fat controllers
            are gone. But coolify's ApplicationDeploymentJob (4,894 LOC), bagisto's Cart.php (1,204 LOC), and
            invoiceninja's PdfBuilder (2,410 LOC) prove that complex operations will always find a container.
            Decomposition is a discipline applied at every level, not a one-time architectural decision.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="lesson-item">
        <div class="lesson-num">04</div>
        <div>
          <div class="lesson-title">Package constraints force the decisions application developers avoid</div>
          <p class="lesson-body">
            subscriptionify (5K LOC package) scores 8.20 — higher than every full application except koel and monica.
            Package development mandates interface contracts, injectable dependencies, config-driven behaviour, and
            isolated testability. These are exactly the decisions large application codebases accumulate as technical
            debt when left optional. Building a package before a feature is a practical forcing function.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="lesson-item">
        <div class="lesson-num">05</div>
        <div>
          <div class="lesson-title">PHPStan error density measures implicit PHP, not absolute quality</div>
          <p class="lesson-body">
            From a root scan without project-specific configs: invoiceninja gets 2 errors, akaunting gets 1,
            but coolify gets 22,065 and subscriptionify 593. This doesn't mean invoiceninja is 11,000× better.
            It means invoiceninja's code is more explicit — fewer unresolved facade calls and Laravel magic methods.
            Coolify's architecture relies more on globally-autoloaded helpers PHPStan can't resolve without a project
            bootstrap. Error density here measures how much the project relies on Laravel's magic — a real signal,
            but not the complete picture.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

    </div>
  </div>
</section>

